sentences: Paul Augustus Csonka (24 October 1905 – 24 November 1995) was an Austrian composer and opera conductor.
In 1973, he was awarded the highest artistic honor the Austrian Government grants: the Cross of honor.
The following year(1974)
The following year(1974)
Summers were spent in Brioni, Semmering, or Mattsee, enjoying the good life with the famous Austrian families of the era, including the Wittgensteins, the von Sturgkhs, and the von Ruesslers.
It was only in his thirties that he chose to leave the world of finance and pursue his one love: music.
In 1934 Csonka founded the Salzburg Opera Guild under the supervision of Sol Hurok and with the support of Arturo Toscanini, Otto Klemperer, Stefan Zweig, Albert Schweizer, and Ernst Krenek.
In 1958, when the revolution started in Cuba, the division and occupation of Europe was fresh in Csonka's head and he had no interest in dealing with political upheaval again.
After being approached by Fidel Castro in 1962 to become National Director of Music, Csonka was quoted, "To work under communism is terrible, but to work with communists is impossible".
Csonka immediately informed Castro that he had been invited to conduct a concert in Miami, Florida for a weekend and would be returning shortly.
He took only a small weekend suitcase and a briefcase and again left a life of wealth, with only his music and his personality, to flee again to a foreign country, aged 58.
Marcel Prawy said "Paul Csonka could be set down on the moon, and within months they would have an opera company."
Indeed, within months of his arrival in Miami, he was approached to start an opera company in Palm Beach.
In the early 1970s, he also orchestrated songs for the folk singer, Cat Stevens.
Concierto de Navidad, composed in 1958 (multiple recordings available)
Concerto Cubano, composed c. 1950
Santa Lucia Variation, composed in 1955
The Lannan Suite Ballet, composed in 1978
The Little Prince Suite, composed 1975
The Bartered Bride, by Smetana (E.F. Kalmus 1968)
